OPERATION OF CLASS 4848 DRIP SYSTEM CONTROL PANELS 
 
 
 
 
A. 
When the bottom permissive float makes, the dosing timer will start in the off  
 
 
cycle. At the end of the off time, the pump will start, the main valve will close and  
 
 
filter 1 valve will open for an adjustable time thus backwashing filter 1. At the end  
 
 
of filter 1 backwashing, filter 2 will backwash for an adjustable time. This will  
 
 
continue until all filters are backwashed. The closing of the main valve allows for  
 
 
all pumped water to be available for backwash. 
 
 
B. 
After the filters backwash, the main valve opens. At the same time, field 1 valve  
 
 
opens and 1 doses for an adjustable time. After field 1 doses, field 2 doses  
 
 
for an adjustable time. All subsequent fields dose similarly one after another in  
 
 
sequence. The pump continues to run from initial start to last field dose. 
 
 
C. 
After an adjustable number of complete dosing cycles, each field will back flush.  
 
 
Back flushing is done after each individual field finishes dosing and before the  
 
 
next field in the sequence begins dosing. 
 
D. 
During dosing, should the filters differential pressure switch detect that the filters 
need to be backwashed, then a filter backwash sequence will commence the 
same as the backwash done at the beginning of the run cycle. The main valve 
will close, the filter valves will open in proper sequence and all of the filters will 
backwash. After backwash, the fields will continue to dose beginning with the 
next field in the sequence where it left off. If the filters are still not clean, then 
another filter backwash will be called for. The system will allow for a maximum of 
B74 “in-dosing” backwashing of filters per cycle. Afterwards an alarm will occur 
and no more PD backwashes will be allowed until manually reset. This is to 
prevent sending excess water back to the head of the plant. There is a B73 time 
delay after the PD switch operates before a PD backwash will start. While 
alarming, normal operation including backwashing at the beginning of each cycle, 
will still occur. 
 
 
E. 
Each pump and valve can be independently operated using the Hand-Off- 
 
 
Automatic (HOA) switches. Make sure all operating systems switches are placed  
 
 
back in Automatic before leaving the site. Indicating lights are on when a valve is  
 
 
open or a pump motor starter is engaged. The main valve is a normally open  
 
 
valve, so its red light is on when it is closed.  
 
 
F. 
Alarms occur for high water level, low water level and filter pressure differential  
 
 
lock-out. Level alarms automatically reset when they are corrected. The filter  
 
 
pressure differential alarm requires manual reset.

Upon power up the clock screen may not be displayed. The screen is considered the “main” screen and 
will be the starting point for all programming.  
 
Locating the clock screen: 
Use the “DOWN” key to scroll until the clock screen is shown. 
 
To enter into program mode press “ESC” once. (See chart 1)  Arrow down to desired selection and press 
“OK”.  
 
x 
To set clock, arrow down to “SET CLOCK” and press “OK”. Use “LEFT” and “RIGHT” arrow 
keys to maneuver around and the “UP” and “DOWN” keys to change setting. Once complete press 
“OK”. To get back to main screen press “ESC”. 
 
x 
To set parameters, arrow down to “SET PARAMETERS” and press “OK”. Use “UP” and 
“DOWN” arrow keys to scroll through blocks. Once desired block is found press “OK”. Use 
“LEFT” and “RIGHT” arrow keys to maneuver around and the “UP and “DOWN” keys to 
change the parameter. Once parameter is set press “OK”. Now you may continue to scroll the 
blocks. Once scrolling is complete press “ESC”. To return to the main screen press “ESC” again. 
 
Chart 1 
Notes:  
1) To view inputs, at the main screen (clock showing) press the “RIGHT” arrow key. To return to 
main screen press “LEFT” arrow key. 
2) To view outputs, at the main screen (clock showing) press the “RIGHT” arrow key twice. To 
return to main screen press “LEFT” arrow key twice.      
     3)  Earlier versions of the PLC had the inputs, outputs and clock on the    
          main screen upon  power up.

CP-4850 TITAN DEHUMIDIFIER-TEST PROCEDURE
1.) Test Box: switches between      &      - Water in Fuel light
                                                       &      - Drive box temp switch
                                                       &      - Humidistat
                                                       &      - Heater t-stat
                                                       &      - Control power "e-stop"
                                                       &      - Gas Monitor
2.) 12VDC Power Supply to
      terminals 2(-) & 4(+).
3.) Schneider overload usually
      comes tripped from factory
      -reset it or will not work.
4.) 240V, 1Ø pigtail on dist.
     block
5.) Check voltage from dist. block to each breaker - verify correct leg.
6.) Check voltage through contactors/overloads.
7.) Verify 8 gauge neutral run to L3 of RC1.
8.) Verify mechanical interlock between  RC1 & HC1.
9.) Check voltage on terminals 60 & 61 from CB6 - Verify ground 62.
10.) Check voltage on terminals 63 & 64 from CB7.
11.) Check voltage on terminal 30 to neutral from CB8.
12.) Check voltage on terminals 31 & 32 from CB5 through CR8.
12.) Check voltage on terminals 31 & 32 from CB5 through CR8.
13.) Verify terminal 3 is jumped to terminal 1 & all 2 terminals are jumped together.
14.) Verify 12VDC on terminals 4 & 2.
15.) Flip test switch between terminals 29 & 30 to ON position - Emergency Stop control power.
16.) Verify white control power light is on & ETM is counting.
17.) Flip test switch between terminals 25 & 26 to ON position - Heater Thermostat.
18.) Verify Heater-aux power switch is turned to HEATER position.
19.) Turn OFF - ON switch to ON position.
1.) CR3 will energize causing PLC I2 to de-energize CR3-1 N.O. contact will close but I1 will not energize until
PLC PROCEDURE ONCE SWITCH IS TURNED ON:
Test Parameters:
B001 - 06:00s
B002 - 00:10m
B003 - 00:20m
     CR8-1 (Reactivation Blower) energizes.
2.) The above step causes reactivation blower (M2) to pull in immediately which will energize I1 (CR8-1) - CHECK RUN LIGHT.
3.) I1 energized will trigger (B001 - 6sec) delay then pull in process blower starter (M1). - CHECK RUN LIGHT
4.) I1 also triggers TD3 to begin counting (set to 5 sec for testing). TD3 expires and pulls HC1 & HC2 in as long as thermostat toggle is ON.
5.) Flip thermostat toggle OFF/ON back & forth to watch HC1 & HC2 drop out & pull in.
6.) Turn OFF-ON switch to OFF - HC1/HC2/M1 drop out
                   -M2 stays pulled in to exhaust
                   -Cool down light turns on for exhaust duration (B002 - 10sec)
SUMMARY: ON (0sec) > M2 (B002 - 6sec) > M1 (TD3 - 5sec) > HC1/HC2
TESTING CONTINUED:
20.) Turn system OFF and switch to HEAT - HC1 will be disabled and RC1 will pull in - that is all this switch does
21.) Check voltage (120V) on 27 & 28 terminals - also 120V 69 & 70, 67 & 68 terminals.
22.) Trigger all alarms: OL1 - Shuts everything down immediately, except reactivation blower - runs cool down
                                     OL2 - Shuts everything down immediately, OL2 trips=no cooldown
                                     Humidistat - PLC delay B003, shuts everything down immediately, except reactivation blower - runs cool down
                                     Gas Monitor - TD3, shuts everything down immediately, except reactivation blower - runs cool down
                                     Drive lost T.S. - TD2, shuts everything down immediately, except reactivation blower - runs cool down
23.) Check 12VDC between terminals: 17 & 18, 3 & 2 , +12 & -12, 9 & 2.
24.) Test WIF light w/ toggle switch on terminals 2 & 10.
25.) Check continuity from terminal strip to door terminals for DEEP SEA.
TD Test Parameters:
TD1: 10sec
TD2: 3sec

Upon power up the clock screen may not be displayed. The screen is considered the “main” screen and 
will be the starting point for all programming.  
 
Locating the clock screen: 
Use the “DOWN” key to scroll until the clock screen is shown. 
 
To enter into program mode press “ESC” once. (See chart 1)  Arrow down to desired selection and press 
“OK”.  
 
 To set clock, arrow down to “SET CLOCK” and press “OK”. Use “LEFT” and “RIGHT” arrow 
keys to maneuver around and the “UP” and “DOWN” keys to change setting. Once complete press 
“OK”. To get back to main screen press “ESC”. 
 
 To set parameters, arrow down to “SET PARAMETERS” and press “OK”. Use “UP” and 
“DOWN” arrow keys to scroll through blocks. Once desired block is found press “OK”. Use 
“LEFT” and “RIGHT” arrow keys to maneuver around and the “UP and “DOWN” keys to 
change the parameter. Once parameter is set press “OK”. Now you may continue to scroll the 
blocks. Once scrolling is complete press “ESC”. To return to the main screen press “ESC” again. 
 
Chart 1 
Notes:  
1) To view inputs, at the main screen (clock showing) press the “RIGHT” arrow key. To return to 
main screen press “LEFT” arrow key. 
2) To view outputs, at the main screen (clock showing) press the “RIGHT” arrow key twice. To 
return to main screen press “LEFT” arrow key twice.      
     3)  Earlier versions of the PLC had the inputs, outputs and clock on the    
          main screen upon  power up.  
 
Word/Setting the PLC with view of PLC  
Earlier versions of the PLC required different key combinations to enter into  
program  mode, with the clock showing, press the following: 
 
PLC Identification 
OBA00   
Press “OK” and “LEFT” and “RIGHT” arrow keys (at the same time) 
OBA1 – OBA2   Press “ESC” and “OK” keys (at the same time) 
OBA3 – OBA6   Press “ESC” key (once)
